preToolUse[Task] instead |\\n| `postToolUseFailure` | ✅ | ❌ | Not implemented |\\n| `beforeShellExecution` | ✅ | ❌ | Not implemented |\\n| `afterFileEdit` | ✅ | ❌ | Not implemented |\\n| `preCompact` | ✅ | ❌ | Not implemented |\\n\\n**Notable Differences from Docs:**\\n\\n1. **Session ID Fallback** - PR uses `conversation_id` as fallback when `session_id` is missing (types.go:44-49). The docs show `conversation_id` and `session_id` as separate fields, so this fallback is a defensive design choice.\\n\\n2. **Hook Config Location** - PR only supports project-level `.cursor/hooks.json`. Cursor docs mention three priority levels (enterprise, project, user). This is fine for project-specific tooling.\\n\\n3. **Subagent Hooks** - PR uses `preToolUse/postToolUse` with `Task` matcher instead of the dedicated `subagentStart/subagentStop` hooks. Both approaches work, but using the dedicated hooks would be more semantic.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Comparison with Competing PR #260\\n\\nPR #260 from 9bany and PR #392 both touch similar files:\\n\\n| Aspect | PR #260 | PR #392 |\\n|--------|---------|---------|\\n| Files | 13 files | 11 files |\\n| Architecture | Adds separate handlers file | Self-contained in `agent/cursor/` |\\n| Hook registration | Uses `hook_registry.go` | Uses package `init()` pattern |\\n| Testing | No tests visible | 11 hook tests + 12 lifecycle tests |\\n| Status | Draft | Open |\\n\\n**Key Architectural Difference:** PR #392 keeps all Cursor logic inside `cmd/entire/cli/agent/cursor/`, following the same pattern as `claudecode/`. PR #260 spreads implementation across `hooks_cursor_handlers.go` in the parent `cli` package.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Key Design Decisions in PR #392\\n\\n#### 1. **Reuse of JSONL Transcript Infrastructure**\\n\\n```go\\n// cursor.go:177-180\\nlines, err := transcript.ParseFromBytes(data)\\n```\\n\\nDecision: Cursor uses the same JSONL transcript format as Claude Code, so the PR reuses the existing `transcript` package rather than writing new